<subSubSection id="48F3ACD6240C741649C03710AC60CBD3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="description">
<paragraph id="C4A5A7B62E1C04088C3201C478992358" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B53077729B87C7FE809052FDEFB95C63" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Body flattened dorso-ventrally. Disk small, with five long and narrow arms (~4.93 mm) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B098210CD376436CDBAB56929D0E5F61" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Some species of the family Astropectinidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Astropecten alligator (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail of the paxilla B Actinal view, in detail of mouth C Abactinal view of the arm D Actinal view of the arm; Astropecten cingulatus (E-H) E Abactinal view, in detail the paxilla F Actinal view G Abactinal view of the arm, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="5" pageNumber="6">5a, b</figureCitation>
). Epiproctal cone pronounced (this region of the disk and the surrounding areas are inflated) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D15FDB4B05A07CC7120760224784A10D" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Some species of the family Astropectinidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Astropecten alligator (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail of the paxilla B Actinal view, in detail of mouth C Abactinal view of the arm D Actinal view of the arm; Astropecten cingulatus (E-H) E Abactinal view, in detail the paxilla F Actinal view G Abactinal view of the arm, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="5" pageNumber="6">5a</figureCitation>
). Abactinal surface flat and covered by small paxillae disposed in regular rows (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B94BECCEE692AC3FA2A485223E1222DC" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Some species of the family Astropectinidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Astropecten alligator (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail of the paxilla B Actinal view, in detail of mouth C Abactinal view of the arm D Actinal view of the arm; Astropecten cingulatus (E-H) E Abactinal view, in detail the paxilla F Actinal view G Abactinal view of the arm, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="5" pageNumber="6">5a</figureCitation>
). Paxillae with a central spinelet and 8-10 (usually 9) thick, marginal spinelets with blunts extremities. Superomarginal figs short (~1.14 mm) and narrow (~1.59 mm), covered by short and blunt spinelets, giving a granulose appearance to animals. Each of these figs has an elongate, conical and pointed spine (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4E798C508F58E2498060B5AD16C05C78" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Some species of the family Astropectinidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Astropecten alligator (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail of the paxilla B Actinal view, in detail of mouth C Abactinal view of the arm D Actinal view of the arm; Astropecten cingulatus (E-H) E Abactinal view, in detail the paxilla F Actinal view G Abactinal view of the arm, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="5" pageNumber="6">5a, c</figureCitation>
), which has the same length from the interbrachial area to the extremity of each arm. Inferomarginal figs with two long, flattened and pointed spines, placed in parallel to each other. These figs are also covered by short and narrow spinelets. Towards the mouth the inferomarginal figs are covered by many flattened and pointed spines, which become elongated at the margins. Adambulacral figs with three long, flattened adambulacral spines, placed in parallel to each other, the median one being slightly longer than the other two (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4F67E6F1397F37CF8FC3AA63E75AA3C6" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Some species of the family Astropectinidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Astropecten alligator (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail of the paxilla B Actinal view, in detail of mouth C Abactinal view of the arm D Actinal view of the arm; Astropecten cingulatus (E-H) E Abactinal view, in detail the paxilla F Actinal view G Abactinal view of the arm, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="5" pageNumber="6">5d</figureCitation>
). There are three to four long and flattened subambulacral spines, the median of which is longer and wider than the other two.
</paragraph>
<caption id="951BB10929B5D5C0F05BAD10440A2309" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" start="Figure 5" startId="F5">
<paragraph id="FEE35F7AEEBCBB165742A11101441E29" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis id="D73DDE83D3A95981FFFC53742C8A3CC5" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Figure 5.</emphasis>
Some species of the family 
<taxonomicName id="334CBFC20109BA56FD2E4683E0DFA2A3" authorityName="J.E.Gray" authorityYear="1840" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Astropectinidae</taxonomicName>
recorded in northeastern Brazil. 
<taxonomicName id="D0696F6B949B57074D9A71D825BAA6E3" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1881" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten alligator" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="alligator">
<emphasis id="1E47FB91BBC515100AEA1DF801B1B564" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten alligator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="D5C991A379731D2F6CB455F3433EED20" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">(A-D)</emphasis>
<emphasis id="817C8C219757E6A94FCCDDE16D9E4A6C" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">A</emphasis>
Abactinal view, in detail of the paxilla 
<emphasis id="FB9D96A88412B5F552DCC6086490837E" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">B</emphasis>
Actinal view, in detail of mouth 
<emphasis id="ADDC72A7DECE33B0E9F972D3129DAB20" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">C</emphasis>
Abactinal view of the arm 
<emphasis id="46DD361361A0333009791AEFCDD93250" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">D</emphasis>
Actinal view of the arm; 
<taxonomicName id="209BA38CA006515F82021E13864199B4" authorityName="Sladen" authorityYear="1833" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten cingulatus" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cingulatus">
<emphasis id="043AB448FA0E83775A50357F644F1D74" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten cingulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="1157ADCD1D0119A2D3DE2DF695D76203" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">(E-H)</emphasis>
<emphasis id="0CB71A0D23E9F0C6A36ADE0E1FF66342" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">E</emphasis>
Abactinal view, in detail the paxilla 
<emphasis id="E073BE7EFF1BF2A0B858EDFE6B4E495E" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">F</emphasis>
Actinal view 
<emphasis id="798681AB51898041F4366ACA35B8A428" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">G</emphasis>
Abactinal view of the arm, and 
<emphasis id="0E3245BB347DFD512CFE57432A4EF08F" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">H</emphasis>
Actinal view of the arm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="53E84152D4DAF50820CECAC7E9324A64" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis id="9EC2F966E521FD4AD8D3D5A4569C4FCF" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Colour.</emphasis>
Reddish-brown dorsally, with conspicuous dark bands along the center of each arm (
<bibRefCitation id="1DCA945FD7D3D2536FAADE2E9AD5BC74" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
), or uniformly orange-red.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DB813DFF03E15681A7DCDC8E0F014775" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E656FADD8B323B15FF27B6D42CD9BCE1" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="08FE998C198A1812F3D201D879B02034" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
North Carolina, the Bahamas, Florida, Honduras, Nicaragua Colombia, and Brazil (
<bibRefCitation id="C6DF66A05841A285013296EF4F79E2ED" author="Verrill, AE" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin from the Laboratories of Natural History of the State University of Iowa" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 232" refId="B151" refString="Verrill, AE, 1915. Report on the starfishes of the West Indies, Florida, and Brazil, including those obtained by Bahamas Expedition from the University of Iowa in 1893. Bulletin from the Laboratories of Natural History of the State University of Iowa 7: 1 - 232" title="Report on the starfishes of the West Indies, Florida, and Brazil, including those obtained by Bahamas Expedition from the University of Iowa in 1893." volume="7" year="1915">Verrill 1915</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="E504E832419C81D87112C18D5892DF74" author="Gray, IE" journalOrPublisher="Fishery Bulletin" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="127 - 163" refId="B50" refString="Gray, IE, Downey, ME, Cerame-Vivas, MJ, 1968. Sea-stars of North Carolina. Fishery Bulletin 67: 127 - 163" title="Sea-stars of North Carolina." volume="67" year="1968">Gray et al. 1968</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A4462C9A54C5FE087FBD433F8D93D5CB" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F5A1277D09A161D878CC0FB186729CBB" author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="171 - 194" refId="B11" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Solano, OD, Navas, GR, 2005. Listado taxonomico de los asteroideos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) de la plataforma y talud superior del Caribe colombiano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 53: 171 - 194" title="Listado taxonomico de los asteroideos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) de la plataforma y talud superior del Caribe colombiano." volume="53" year="2005">Benavides-Serrato et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="5DE72F60CA0C756062F56DA2FAA3177E" author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refId="B12" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Dias Sanchez, CM, 2011. Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea. Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" title="Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea." year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F23AED652435E68589831CF25E164528" author="Alvarado, JJ" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="37 - 55" refId="B4" refString="Alvarado, JJ, Solis-Marin, FA, Ahearn, C, 2008. Equinodermos (Echinodermata) del Caribe Centroamericano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 56: 37 - 55" title="Equinodermos (Echinodermata) del Caribe Centroamericano." volume="56" year="2008">Alvarado et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
). In Brazil: 
<bibRefCitation id="D30EF7E6E023CE40B23A3D2EA3306C35" author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="171 - 194" refId="B11" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Solano, OD, Navas, GR, 2005. Listado taxonomico de los asteroideos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) de la plataforma y talud superior del Caribe colombiano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 53: 171 - 194" title="Listado taxonomico de los asteroideos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) de la plataforma y talud superior del Caribe colombiano." volume="53" year="2005">Benavides-Serrato et al. (2005)</bibRefCitation>
cite its occurrence in the north of Brazil. This study expands the distribution southward to the State of 
<normalizedToken id="0AD3C187E06B7B75FC2E836B326102D5" originalValue="Paraíba">Paraiba</normalizedToken>
, being the first reference for the northeast region of Brazil. From 22 to 576 m in depth (
<bibRefCitation id="CF9AE00120A6C2D016C3F3554C307A09" author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refId="B12" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Dias Sanchez, CM, 2011. Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea. Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" title="Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea." year="2011">Benavides-Serrato et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
), most frequent between 22 and 114 m (
<bibRefCitation id="67EBB169BE2C102148E338AB208D2B51" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="380FC2ED9845C1160127CFD20D3E7780" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="F3093D99B0DB1D7D77BB188FF10B06EE" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="787FEF69825021DA4F995DE55845303A" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName id="2B8F4C289F82635502DF3A13F7750B3F" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1881" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten alligator" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="alligator">
<emphasis id="3C51D5E628173F504C4B456A7589170A" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten alligator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
difers from the remaining species in the genus recorded for Brazil for presenting a single, elongate, erect conical spine on all the superomarginal figs. This character is present in both juvenile and adult individuals (dd = 41.0 mm). For a long time it was believed that 
<bibRefCitation id="5C4E53EDAF88F25B0868AE6949E6F5FF" author="Perrier, E" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 31" refId="B118" refString="Perrier, E, 1881. Reports on the results of dredging by the United States coast survey Steaner &quot;Blake&quot;. XIV. Description sommaire des speces nouvelles d'Asteries. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology 9: 1 - 31" title="Reports on the results of dredging by the United States coast survey Steaner &quot; Blake &quot;. XIV. Description sommaire des speces nouvelles d'Asteries." volume="9" year="1881">Perrier (1881)</bibRefCitation>
had described 
<taxonomicName id="D9BAAC42121DC27880EA304111D9CC94" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1881" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten alligator" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="alligator">
<emphasis id="959C294958B9692031496BD29802936F" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten alligator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a juvenile specimen and the recognition of this species remained uncertain. 
<bibRefCitation id="679A332430D46243D48E53CF532BCEDD" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey (1992)</bibRefCitation>
analised the type material of 
<taxonomicName id="BA88B40363FC50BAFB11CD3133DBDD55" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1881" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten alligator" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="alligator">
<emphasis id="9BB72EB0A712757AE7B77C4B0C9E8B58" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten alligator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They were able to validate the species and consider 
<taxonomicName id="D8F183B2367C75B207F8493325A9F735" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1915" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten nuttingi" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="nuttingi">
<emphasis id="9857018871BB8D3B44E6898FEB0AA08B" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten nuttingi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Verrill, 1915 a junior synonym of this taxon. In a molecular phylogenetic analysis of 
<taxonomicName id="54E279D10AFAD0995E8471614F41065E" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="433206A6A98076DB31E634D564E19892" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A9883A3DC87FA5969E9C2AFDDFC0002C" author="Zulliger, DE" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 19" refId="B159" refString="Zulliger, DE, Lessios, HA, 2010. Phylogenetic relationships in the genus Astropecten Gray (Paxillosida: Astropectinidae) on global scale: molecular evidence for morphological convergence, species-complexes and possible cryptic speciation. Zootaxa 19: 1 - 19" title="Phylogenetic relationships in the genus Astropecten Gray (Paxillosida: Astropectinidae) on global scale: molecular evidence for morphological convergence, species-complexes and possible cryptic speciation." volume="19" year="2010">Zulliger and Lessios (2010)</bibRefCitation>
concluded that 
<taxonomicName id="9DFA14E89CA438C53F9118E95780F41E" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1881" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten alligator" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="alligator">
<emphasis id="4390489D11530277710342A830BF2EE8" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten alligator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E5DD4E0CF4ACC5ADA219455643BA900B" baseAuthorityName="Verrill" baseAuthorityYear="1880" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten americanus" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="americanus">
<emphasis id="F15999C1AAF4023E077AA501697584D9" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten americanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably belong to the same species and that the species needs to be extensively revised.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="330B803333317E90C88CDDEF4C6D3D41" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="ecological notes">
<paragraph id="0A693C276CCEAC464E897C7EE05FA8FC" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Ecological notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1CEED6028D2C109B51F1CDCB43A7077D" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Usually inhabits muddy environments, but may also be found associated to communities of azooxanthelate corals (
<bibRefCitation id="46E7771A4B750C10CB5CCB5F8507793C" author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refId="B12" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Dias Sanchez, CM, 2011. Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea. Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" title="Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea." year="2011">Benavides-Serrato et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). It is common along the coast of Florida (
<bibRefCitation id="3CA5EEE9E729FF16D191FF42D10DFD40" author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
), but for a long time it has been erroneously cited there as 
<taxonomicName id="2EAC956551CF766AFC32C7D8E5ABED57" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1915" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten nuttingi" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="nuttingi">
<emphasis id="80E424461ACDD15D0B0C4F6C22962B06" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten nuttingi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In other areas 
<taxonomicName id="1B97EF54E21992A9D44D78AFA4D44D61" authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1881" class="Asteroidea" family="Astropectinidae" genus="Astropecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Astropecten alligator" order="Paxillosida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="alligator">
<emphasis id="C23176DE24F790F258E4A24502E9C275" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Astropecten alligator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare species, being little cited in the literature.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
